Process Description (SUPO)

The primary purpose of the Trona Facility's SUPO Plant is the production of Potassium Sulfate.  As part of its operations, the SUPO Plant operates an anhydrous ammonia-based refrigeration system.  The refrigeration system contains approximately 11,510 pounds of anhydrous ammonia in a closed loop process.  The system, consisting of piping, valves, and equipment, cycles ammonia through various physical states (high pressure liquid, low pressure liquid, low pressure vapor, high pressure vapor, then back to high pressure liquid) to provide refrigeration chilling of glycol which is used in the manufacture of Potassium Sulfate.  The refrigeration system (i.e., the use of anhydrous ammonia) is a 24-hour per day, 365-day per year operation that is essential to manufacturing operations conducted at the SUPO Plant.  



The anhydrous ammonia storage, handling and use system at the SUPO Plant consists of the following major components:

?    Two ammonia brine condensers;

?    One ammonia centrate condenser;

?    Three ammonia compressors;

?    The main high-pressure receiver;

?    Vertical flash economizer;

?    Pump out accumulator vessel;

?    Three plate and frame flooded chillers with associated accumulators;

?    An evaporator;

?    Two glycol pumps;

?    Water diffusion tank;

?    Transfer piping and supports; and

?    Process instrumentation, detection and monitoring devices.



Water Based Anhydrous Ammonia Diffusion System

